      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "cf596fa9488954b7",
      "text": "As we write in an __extreme literate programming__ environment, we are not simply in the world of code, we are also writing prose and working with media. Just as importantly we are no longer isolated authors, rather we are engaged in a wiki-like process of [[collaborative writing]]. Extreme literate programming is therefore social.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "dd1b8cf1f62a1e22",
      "text": "# Why\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "516006c66206c49c",
      "text": "Why should we consider extreme literate [[coding]]? After all the more we have to type, the more chances to make a mistake. And as we know programmers hate typing - there is a great quote here from the land of lisp / perl I can't quite track down.\n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "8b443d5f14954211",
      "text": "The other motivation for this work is the understanding that in a time of democratic governance, a modern [[language of power]] needs to be literate. \n"
    },
    {
      "type": "markdown",
      "id": "d1b35bca9ce0f00c",
      "text": "It is not enough to rely on an elite to create the code that runs our society, we all need to be able to read it, write it and help improve the design. A literate and [[performative code]] is the fabric on top of which a modern society is able to realise itself."
    },
